[Case 3 Round 2 Step 2] CANDIDATE: {"response": {"action": "request", "request": "Please provide the following additional clinical and diagnostic information to refine the diagnosis and guide management:\n\n1. **Bone marrow aspiration and biopsy results**, including:\n   - Cellularity (hypo-, normo-, or hypercellular)\n   - Morphology (dysplasia, blast percentage, presence of ring sideroblasts, fibrosis)\n   - Cytogenetics (karyotype, FISH for common MDS-associated abnormalities such as del(5q), -7/del(7q), +8, del(20q))\n   - Flow cytometry (to assess for aberrant myeloid or lymphoid populations)\n   - Molecular studies (e.g., mutations in *SF3B1*, *TET2*, *ASXL1*, *DNMT3A*, or *TP53* if MDS is suspected)\n\n2. **Peripheral blood flow cytometry** (if not already performed) to evaluate for:\n   - Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH) clone (CD55/CD59 deficiency)\n   - Aberrant myeloid or lymphoid populations\n\n3. **Additional laboratory tests**:\n   - **Hemolysis workup**: Direct antiglobulin test (DAT), LDH, haptoglobin, bilirubin (if not already done)\n   - **Infectious workup**: Blood cultures, viral serologies (e.g., HIV, hepatitis B/C, EBV, CMV, parvovirus B19)\n   - **Autoimmune workup**: ANA, rheumatoid factor, complement levels (C3, C4)\n   - **Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria (PNH) testing**: FLAER assay or high-sensitivity flow cytometry for CD55/CD59 deficiency\n\n4. **Imaging**:\n   - **Chest X-ray** (to assess for infection, mediastinal lymphadenopathy, or other abnormalities)\n   - **Abdominal ultrasound or CT scan** (to evaluate for splenomegaly, hepatomegaly, lymphadenopathy, or other organ involvement)\n\n5. **Detailed medication history**:\n   - Recent exposure to chemotherapy, radiation, or other myelotoxic drugs\n   - Use of antibiotics (e.g., sulfa drugs, chloramphenicol), antiepileptics, or other medications associated with marrow suppression\n\n6. **Functional and nutritional assessment**:\n   - Nutritional status (e.g., albumin, prealbumin, vitamin levels)\n   - Performance status (e.g., ECOG or Karnofsky score) to guide treatment decisions."}}
